Harvard students take courses on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year encourages students to sleep more, in an attempt to fight growing "macho" culture that makes them subject to "all night" learning sessions, energized with a lot of caffeine.
A scientist has discovered that, often, students of the most prestigious universities in the world do not even master the basic concepts of how they should take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the one who created the course, which is believed to be the first of this type in the USA.
It was inspired to create the course after holding a conference on the impact of sleeplessness on the ability to learn.
“At the end, a girl came in and said to me, ‘Why is this being said to me just now, in the last year?’
She told me that she had never been told about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," she said to The Telegraph.
The course, first introduced this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance as well as the general good condition.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the university, said that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course may involve a number of interactive tasks.
Within a section is presented the image of a home room, and students can click on coffee cans, curtains, sports pants and cards to tell them what the effects of caffeine and light are and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deficiency, but also about the importance of a sleep program.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive pictograms, encourages participants to think about their daily program.
"We know we can't change students' behavior instantly.
But we believe that they have the right to know, just as anyone has the right to know what the effects of smoking on health are," added Professor Czeisler.
Culture that makes students proud that they have learned all night still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure imposed by students have turned sleep deprivation into a growing problem.
Sufficient sleep, of good quality, should be a "secret weapon" of a student to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, said this, even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation makes the brain think that the body is hungry, which makes the students feel that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler create the course after he attended one of his courses in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course for all students.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all post-university students to complete a similar study programme before enrolling in this institution where competition is successful.
Professor Czeisler advised students to schedule an alarm to know when it is time to sleep, as well as for waking time, and to know what are the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LEDs, which can disturb the circadian rhythm and cause difficulties when they try to sleep.
