HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in the number of new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of Chinese citizens suffering from HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected by this disease in China, officials say.
About 40,000 new cases were reported only in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases have been sexually transmitted, unlike in the past.
In the past, HIV has spread rapidly in some areas of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
But the number of people who have contracted HIV in this way has been reduced to almost zero, say Chinese health officials at a conference in Yunnan Province.
From one year to another, however, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
Sexually transmitted HIV is an acute problem in China's LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is considered widespread.
Because of the country's conservative values, studies estimate that 70-90% of men who have sex with other men will eventually end up marrying a woman.
Many cases of disease transmission are derived from inadequate sexual protection measures in such relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV drugs as part of its efforts to solve the problem.
