The Global Citizens' Festival, launched in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy group that hopes to eliminate poverty by increasing the number of people who are actively fighting against it.
In order to receive a free ticket at the event (except if they are willing to pay for a VIP ticket), spectators had to pay for a series of tasks or "actions", such as volunteering, sending e-mails to world leaders, making phone calls or other significant things that help increase awareness of the global poverty elimination target.
But what success has the Global Citizen's Festival had when it's only 12 years to achieve its goal?
Is it the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a good way to convince them to act or is it just another case of so-called "clicktimism", a concept that refers to people who feel they have done something by signing an online petition or sending a message on Twitter?
According to Global Citizen, since 2011, more than 19 million “actions” have been recorded from its supporters, which have promoted different objectives.
The organization says that these actions have driven world leaders to announce commitments and policies worth more than $37 billion, which will affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
