Five of the victims were tourists from Argentina.
It's been a decade since the last trial of a capital punishment case in New York's Southern District.
The defendant, Khalid Barnes, was accused of killing two drug dealers, but was finally sentenced to life imprisonment in September 2009.
The last capital punishment applied in a federal case in New York took place in 1953 for Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, two husbands executed after they were convicted of conspiracy to commit the spying act for the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
Rosenberg's wives were executed on the electric chair on June 19, 1953.
