How can the trade war between the United States and China be beneficial to Beijing?
The Saves that announced the beginning of the trade war between the United States and China were shocking and, although there seems to be a long way to end it, the disputes between the two countries could be beneficial for Beijing in the long term, experts say.
Donald Trump, the President of the United States, issued the first warning early this year, by imposing taxes on key imports from China, including solar panels, steel and aluminium.
The most important escalation occurred this week with new taxes, which affected products worth 200 billion dollars (£150 billion), effectively applying half of all Chinese goods arriving in the United States.
Beijing has avenged each time, most recently imposing a tax of between 5 and 10 percent for US products worth 60 billion dollars.
China has warned that it will respond to every blow from the United States and it is unlikely that the world's second largest economy will take a step back in the near future.
For Washington to withdraw, China must agree with its demands, but public surrender to the United States would be far too humiliating for Xi Jinping, China's President.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressures of the United States on trade war could support China positively in the long term, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
"The fact that a rapid political decision taken in Washington or Beijing could lead to an economic collapse in both countries would, in fact, be more dangerous than expected so far," said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher focusing on Asia at the Center for New American Security, a group of experts.
Syria is ready for the return of refugees, said Minister for Foreign Affairs
Syria affirms that it is prepared for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help in rebuilding the country devastated by a war that has lasted for more than seven years.
During his speech at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the situation in the country was improving.
"Today, the conditions on the spot are more stable and secure, thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists so that things are back to normal.
Existing conditions allow the voluntary return of refugees to the country they were required to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at day-to-day life and their lives.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians fled the country in 2011, when the war broke out.
Six million people who continue to live in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be pleased to receive aid in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he stressed that conditional assistance or aid from countries sponsored by the insurgency would not be accepted.
