News about the red tide: concentrations decreased in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Wildlife Protection Commission shows a general decrease in red sea concentrations for certain areas of the Tampa Gulf.
According to the Commission, conditions of non-uniform inflorescence are reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – suggesting lower concentrations.
This red sea inflorescence extends on an area of the coast of about 210 km, north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The spots can be found about 16 km away from Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
The average concentrations found in or off Pinellas County were reported last week as well as low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, bottom to high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom to high concentrations to high in Sarasota County or across it, bottom to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, bottom to high concentrations in Lee County and across it and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory irritations continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No cases of respiratory irritation have been reported in the northwest of the U.S. state of Florida in the last week.
